title: Upgrade GIST memory compression nodes, kernels, optimizer rule, and cli

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
**Description**: Extend Gist memory compression to support additional compression formats, support of new priority execution order, and other upgrades:

- New Feature: GistPack1 compression. It compresses from float32/bool to 1 bit. It is used for lossless compression for dropout and relu nodes.
- New Feature: GistPack8 compression. It compresses from 32 bits/16 bits to 8 bits. It is used for lossy compression for any operator.
- New Feature: GistPackMsfp15 compression. It compresses 8 (or tile size) values each 32 bits wide to 8 (or tile size) values each 7 bits wide (sign and mantissa) and a single 8 bits shared exponent. It is used for lossy compression for any operator.
- New Feature: GistPack16 compression. It compresses from 32 bits to 16 bits. It is used for lossy compression for any operator.
- We also upgraded Gist rule to support different operators. We created a generic Gist rule as long as we provide a Pattern map. The pattern map has key as the target operator and value as the destination operator (e.g. PATTER_MAP[Sofmax] = {“SoftmaxGrad”}. Our rule is operator-agnostic, and makes Gist robust to support new operators in the future.
- New test for Priority execution order for nested compression.
- Gist upgrade to support priority execution order to trigger encoder (compression) and decoder (decompression) accordingly.
- Gist CLI: --use_gist, --op <which operator is being targeted, e.g. Softmax is op 1> --gist_compr <GistPack1|GistPack8|GistPack16|GistPackMsfp15>

**Motivation and Context**
- *Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?*
It fixes and improves Gist optimizer rule by changing Gist operators to handle 1 input and 1 output without the need of early encoder input or late decoder output. It also adds new compression format (Pack1, Pack8).

title: Avoid false sharing on thread pool data structures
body:
**Description**: This change adds alignment and padding to avoid false sharing on fields in the thread pool.  It also adds a new microbenchmark to profile thread-pool performance over short loops.

**Motivation and Context**
MobileNet on a 2*12-core system showed a performance gap between the ORT thread pool and OpenMP.  One cause appeared to be false sharing on fields in the thread pool: ThreadPoolParallelSection::tasks_finished (which the main thread spins on waiting for workers to complete a loop), and the RunQueue::front_ and back_ fields (used respectively by the worker thread and the main thread).

The additional micro-benchmark BM_ThreadPoolSimpleParallelFor tests performance of loops of different sizes at different thread counts.  The results below are on a machine with 2*14-core processors (E5-2690 v4) running with 1, 14, 15, and 28 threads.  For each test, the microbenchmark has N threads run a loop with N iterations; hence a perfect result is for the time taken to be constant as additional threads are added (although we will also see power management effects helping at very low thread counts).  The loop durations (100000, 10000, 1000) correspond roughly to 200us, 20us, and 2us on this machine.

body:
I have built onnxruntime from master with CUDA11.0 cudnn8 (cuda-devel) . I found that onnxruntime-gpu works well on cuda-devel environment, but it failed on cuda-runtime when running onnxruntime.InferenceSession() with yolov5 model.
The exp_yolov5.py [code](https://github.com/polar99/onnxruntime-gpu-test/blob/main/exp_yolov5.py)
```
import onnxruntime

onnx_path = './yolov5s.onnx'
onnxruntime.InferenceSession(onnx_path, providers=['CUDAExecutionProvider'])
```
The onnxfile [yolov5s_export_false.onnx](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1TxmRqIFcR474vCzaDJhjIS-gBCJPwtRk/view?usp=sharing) (Details of this yolov5s.onnx are in section 3 ) 

### 1. Build based environment in docker containers

**cuda11.0-devel** environment: docker pull nvidia/cuda:11.0-cudnn8-devel-ubuntu18.04
**cuda11.0-runtime** environment: docker pull nvidia/cuda:11.0-cudnn8-runtime-ubuntu18.04

I have install same software both in **cuda11.0-devel** and **cuda11.0-runtime**.
(1) based software
`apt install build-essential zlib1g-dev libncurses5-dev libgdbm-dev libnss3-dev libssl-dev libreadline-dev libffi-dev wget python3-setuptools python3-numpy python3-wheel python python3-pip python3-pytest python3-distutils git curl libgl1-mesa-glx libglib2.0-dev language-pack-en -y`

```
locale-gen en_US.UTF-8
update-locale LANG=en_US.UTF-8
```

(2) Install Python3.8.7 from [here](https://www.python.org/ftp/python/3.8.7/Python-3.8.7.tgz)
(3) Install Cmake3.19.2 from [official cmake website](https://cmake.org/download/)


### 2. Compile onnxruntime-gpu

(1)**cuda-devel** environment: docker pull nvidia/cuda:11.0-cudnn8-devel-ubuntu18.04
The onnxruntime is built from master on this environment.
When running
`python exp_yolov5.py`
onnxruntime works well.

(2)**cuda-runtime** environment: docker pull nvidia/cuda:11.0-cudnn8-runtime-ubuntu18.04
The onnxruntime is built from master on cuda-devel environment.
When running
`python exp_yolov5.py`
onnxruntime will cause fatal error.
Segmentation fault (core dumped)

The following is my building cmd:
`./build.sh --build_shared --parallel --use_cuda --enable_pybind --build_wheel --config Debug--cudnn_home /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/ --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda --cmake_extra_defines PYTHON_LIBRARIES=/usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libpython3.8.so.1.0 PYTHON_EXECUTABLE=/usr/local/bin/python3.8 PYTHON_INCLUDE_DIRS=/usr/local/include/python3.8`

Finally, I got a python wheel then installed onnxruntime_gpu by pip.
`onnxruntime_gpu-1.6.0-cp38-cp38-linux_x86_64.whl`, download here [Google Drive](https://drive.google.com/file/d/18GJ5GbC3KrMUz4KaaSUuPQ5_U77Rp2Ix/view?usp=sharing)


**GDB debug info:** (on cuda-runtime)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23132594/104419791-ee45f080-55b3-11eb-8638-3a63d81bbac0.png)


### 3. About exporting yolov5s.onnx
(1) Download yolov5s.pt from [official release](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5/releases/tag/v4.0) 
(2) Modify [export.py ](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5/blob/v4.0/models/export.py)
In export.py [Line 53](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5/blob/69be8e738f45e7908c1270eedd350f98c0c7bfa4/models/export.py#L53)  
  `model.model[-1].export = True  # set Detect() layer export=True`  
As I want to output post-processed boxes from yolov5 network, I have set 
` model.model[-1].export = False`
This bool value will change the output onnx file.

More details in [yolo.py](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5/blob/v4.0/models/yolo.py)  and the [line](https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov5/blob/69be8e738f45e7908c1270eedd350f98c0c7bfa4/models/yolo.py#L48)
```
            if not self.training:  # inference
                if self.grid[i].shape[2:4] != x[i].shape[2:4]:
                    self.grid[i] = self._make_grid(nx, ny).to(x[i].device)

                y = x[i].sigmoid()
                y[..., 0:2] = (y[..., 0:2] * 2. - 0.5 + self.grid[i].to(x[i].device)) * self.stride[i]  # xy
                y[..., 2:4] = (y[..., 2:4] * 2) ** 2 * self.anchor_grid[i]  # wh
                z.append(y.view(bs, -1, self.no))
```
In conclusion, exported onnx file ([yolov5s_export_false.onnx](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1TxmRqIFcR474vCzaDJhjIS-gBCJPwtRk/view?usp=sharing)) will cause Segmentation fault (core dumped) when `model.model[-1].export = False` on `cuda11.0-runtime`, but running normally on `cuda11.0-devel`.

If applying `model.model[-1].export = True`, exported onnx file ([yolov5s_export_true.onnx](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1YwcLrQx-FpSjI3FftNokNWxLFh8BWdTH/view?usp=sharing)) will running normally both on `cuda11.0-devel` and `cuda11.0-runtime`.

title: Fuse cuda conv with activation
body:
Optimize cuda conv for [ssd](https://github.com/NVIDIA/DeepLearningExamples/tree/master/PyTorch/Detection/SSD#model-architecture) by:

1. Fuse conv->relu into conv;
2. Fuse conv->add->relu into conv.

Perf comparison by cuda 10.1 + cudnn 7.6

Opt | Node count | 100 run
---- | ---- | ----
Before Opt | 203 | 0.87 ms 
After Opt | 80 | 0.68 ms

Note the optimization mainly depends on cudnn function **cudnnconvolutionbiasactivationforward** to perform conv + relu and conv + add + relu in one call. However, for cudnn 8.x, the function is experiencing a notable regression on performance. Test proved that cudnn 7.6 provides the best performance so far:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/48490400/104964045-8f57f100-5990-11eb-9bf6-367216a2e3af.png)
